<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Harvard-Bound UCF Graduate Wins Jack Kent Cooke Scholarship</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">Aug. 8, 2005</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="http://news.ucf.edu/resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE588/en_US/Blair sty.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Courtesy of Kati Blair</p>
			
			<p>Kati Blair, a 2004 UCF graduate and aspiring art teacher, has won one of the nation&#146;s largest graduate scholarships to pay for her studies at Harvard University.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400411a428d50103c2675a0200643a">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Evelyn</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5988</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.jackkentcookefoundation.org/jkcf_web/home.aspx?Page=Main">Jack Kent Cooke Foundation</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.honors.ucf.edu/">UCF Burnett Honors College</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Kati Blair, a 2004 University of Central Florida graduate and aspiring art teacher, has won one of the nationÂ’s largest graduate scholarships to pay for her studies at Harvard University.</p><p>Blair, of <city /><place />Orlando</place /></city />, will receive about $43,000 from the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation to complete a one-year art education graduate program at Harvard beginning in September. The Virginia-based foundation selected 76 winners from 1,290 nominees based on academic achievement, financial need, leadership, community involvement and motivation for success. </p><p /><p /><p>Blair, an honors student who received a bachelorÂ’s degree in art education from UCF in May 2004, taught ceramics classes at <place /><placename />Colonial</placename /> <placetype />High School</placetype /></place /> in <city /><place />Orlando</place /></city /> during the 2004-05 school year. She found success with getting students interested in reading and math through art and with using ceramics to help a diverse group of students appreciate each otherÂ’s cultures.</p><p /><p /><p>Â“I would see students put in religious symbols or symbols of different holidays while making pottery, and I would ask them to explain what they meant,Â” Blair said. Â“It was really neat to see studentsÂ’ cultural values come through in their art.Â”</p><p /><p /><p>At Harvard, Blair wants to continue to explore ways of using contemporary art to help students understand and appreciate other cultures. She also plans to study methods of integrating reading, math and other subjects into art curricula. </p><p /><p /><p>Blair is one of 11 Jack Kent Cooke scholars this year who will attend graduate school at Harvard. Recipients were nominated by their undergraduate institutions and then underwent rigorous assessments by panels consisting of graduate school deans, admissions counselors, faculty and other academic experts. Each scholarship can be worth up to $300,000 over six years.</p><p /><p /><p>After graduate school, Blair, 25, plans to return to teaching art in public schools. She eventually wants to work as a university professor who volunteers as a teacher at a public school so she can continue to work with pupils and stay in touch with the changing needs of public schools.</p><p /><p /><p>Blair Â“wants not only to teach art, but to build connections between the classroom and the community and to work with others who share those values,Â” Alvin Wang, dean of UCFÂ’s <place /><placename />Burnett</placename /> <placename />Honors</placename /> <placetype />College</placetype /></place />, wrote in a letter nominating her. Â“She is particularly dedicated to helping underprivileged students who might otherwise not have access to these educational resources. There is no doubt that this is her passion and her professional Â‘calling.Â’Â”</p><p /><p /><p>In addition to teaching children about art, Blair also wants to inspire them to attend college. She reviewed college essays for many students in her <place /><placename />Colonial</placename /> <placetype />High School</placetype /></place /> classes and spent time during classes answering questions about what college is like and how students should prepare for it.</p><p /><p /><p>Wanting to stay close to home, Blair started her college career at the <place /><placetype />University</placetype /> of <placename />South Florida</placename /></place /> in 1998 after she graduated from <place /><placename />Clearwater</placename /> <placetype />High School</placetype /></place />. She transferred to UCF in 2001 after USF dropped the arts education degree that she had planned to pursue. </p><p /><p /><p>At UCF, Blair made the DeanÂ’s List most semesters and completed an honors-in-the-major thesis on Â“The Role of Contemporary Artists and Mathematics in the Art Classroom.Â” She also was vice president of the UCF chapter of the National Art Education Association.</p><p /><p /><p>Blair served as a student teacher and volunteer math tutor at <place /><placename />Colonial</placename /> <placetype />High School</placetype /></place /> in spring 2004. She also was a student teacher at <place /><placename />Northlake</placename /> <placetype />Park</placetype /> <placetype />Elementary School</placetype /></place /> in <city /><place />Orlando</place /></city /> in fall 2003 and volunteered as a winter art camp teacher at the Orlando Museum of Art in 2003.</p><p /><p /><p>BlairÂ’s father, Hugh, graduated from UCF in 1983 with a bachelorÂ’s degree in engineering technology. He and BlairÂ’s mother, Nanci, live in <city /><place />Orlando</place /></city />.</p><p /><p /><p>Founded in 2000, the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation is a private and independent foundation established by the estate of Jack Kent Cooke to help Â“young people of exceptional promise reach their full potential through education.Â” For more information, visit <span><a href="http://www.jackkentcookefoundation.org">www.jackkentcookefoundation.org</a></span>.</p>
		
	
